    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>132200</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                <p>Cf. for the epitaphs on the opposite side, <bibl><ptr target="#chevrollier-cdl-hussein2021"/>, pp. <citedRange>28-29</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Φοῖνιξ"><supplied reason="lost">Φ</supplied>οῖνιξ</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Ἀντίπατρος"><supplied reason="lost">Ἀ</supplied>ντιπάτρω</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Phoinix fils d'Antipatros.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Phoinix son of Antipatros.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Phoinix figlio di Antipatros.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>Whereas Antipatros is common in Cyrenaica at all periods, Phoinix is here attested for the first time in the region. However it is no rare name in 
               Greece, referring to the ethnic (<bibl><ptr target="#bechtel1917"/>, p. <citedRange>544</citedRange></bibl>) and probably also to the mythologic figure 
                   of Achilleus' tutor.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
